RABIES, CANINE, HUMAN - PHILIPPINES (08): BACKGROUND
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Sat 20 Nov 2010
Source: GIDEON (Global Infectious Disease & Epidemiology Network) [edited]
<http://www.gideononline.com/>


Although the incidence of rabies has declined somewhat in recent
years, disease rates per 100 000 continue to be higher in the
Philippines than in neighboring countries [1,2].

See graph at
<http://www.gideononline.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/Philippines-Rabies.jpg>.

References
----------
1. Berger SA: Infectious Diseases of the Philippines, 2010, 1131 pp.
Gideon e-book series
<http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/country/infectious-diseases-of-the-philippines/>
2. Berger SA: Rabies: Global Status, 2010, 353 pp. Gideon e-book series
<http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/disease/rabies-global-status/>.

--
Communicated by:
Prof Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
Israel
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

[ProMED-mail thanks Professor Berger for providing these data which
document both the progressive decline of rabies cases in the
Philippines and the magnitude of the remaining problem.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Philippines is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/02yD>. - Mod.CP]
